<subSubSection id="76396B3D2C7639712F1755AD9A1683BE" lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A70F057AAA2EB5722CA7797DC6540F61" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="766B1674B602272DEE324F1929A04133" lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
The entirely black head, thorax (including femora and tibiae) and abdomen (whether or not with metallic hues) are shared with five other described 
<taxonomicName id="05D36A0606FD20F26816BE2A6C921C7D" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<pageBreakToken id="A7DB3FFEE44894A286D8A2BFE9A8B0C5" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" start="start">Archimicrodon</pageBreakToken>
</taxonomicName>
-species of the Indo-Australian region (Australia excluded). 
<taxonomicName id="0C5FA258BA9362AB6C1243CE650843AE" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon boharti" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boharti">Archimicrodon boharti</taxonomicName>
(Curran, 1947) (Solomon Islands) differs from this species by the metallic blue shining scutellum, clearly contrasting with the non-metallic mesonotum (in 
<taxonomicName id="2B70FB492777D20F0C9FB01084BFF26B" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon malukensis" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malukensis">Archimicrodon malukensis</taxonomicName>
sp. n. mesonotum and scutellum are of the same black colour). The same character also applies to 
<taxonomicName id="03F18820DFCD5E81E4EF3E250E6FD7C8" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon limbinervis" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbinervis">Archimicrodon limbinervis</taxonomicName>
(de Meijere, 1908) and 
<taxonomicName id="82F285FC15F38997B89BAD182F7303C4" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon incisuralis" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incisuralis">Archimicrodon incisuralis</taxonomicName>
(Walker, 1865) from New Guinea, and 
<taxonomicName id="28B1355545109C119225A22F5473D1C3" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon purpurescens" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurescens">Archimicrodon purpurescens</taxonomicName>
(Shiraki, 1963) from Micronesia, which also differ by the black pilose scutellum (white pilose in 
<taxonomicName id="405B11578641843477EB811655756A4F" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon malukensis" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malukensis">Archimicrodon malukensis</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="BF79D813D4BE3E338B59DB52FB567D74" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon grageti" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grageti">Archimicrodon grageti</taxonomicName>
(de Meijere, 1908) (New Guinea) differs by the brownish abdomen and reddish yellow pregenital segments (black in 
<taxonomicName id="221A4086E5F473B7873FF41823C482A7" authority="Hull, 1945" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1945" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Archimicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Archimicrodon malukensis" order="Diptera" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malukensis">Archimicrodon malukensis</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D8A47B707A943F70D269156A089E0B4A" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" type="description">
<paragraph id="1C64DC014D9341C19B64B3936FD7F4BD" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Description (based on holotype).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3FD0455A061D737DB2759BECC8BF8706" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Adult male. Body size: 8 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CF7839E3D18463B916CEAC007BC9CD0F" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Head. Face occupying about 1/5 of head width in frontal view; black; black pilose, except white pilose on ventral 1/4. Gena hardly developed; black; white pilose. Oral margin not produced. Frons black; black pilose, except white pilose along lateral margin. Vertex black; black pilose. Occiput black; black pilose dorsally, white pilose ventrally. Eye bare. Antennal fossa about as high as wide. Antenna black; antennal ratio approximately as 2:1:3.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="18B1A9708A18CDB36BE9CDFBF1C2B374" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Thorax. Thorax black, except pleurae brownish. Mesoscutum black pilose, except pale yellow pilose along anterior margin, laterally between postpronotum and notopleuron, and in posterolateral corners. Postpronotum pale yellow pilose. Postalar callus black pilose, except pale yellow pilose at posterior apex. Scutellum semicircular, without calcars; entirely pale yellow pilose. Anepisternum with shallow dorsomedian sulcus; white pilose anterodorsally and posterodorsally, widely bare in between. Anterior anepimeron entirely white pilose. Katepimeron sparsely white pilose along dorsal margin, otherwise bare. Katatergum long microtrichose, anatergum short microtrichose. Calypter and halter pale yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EAEDDB448FFAB3CACC233773177EBAE7" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Wing: Hyaline, slightly infuscated antero-apically; microtrichose, except bare on cell sc, basal 1/2 of cell c, basal 2/5 of cell r1, most of cell br except microtrichose along vena spuria, posterobasal 1/5 of cell r4+5, basal 5/6 of cell bm, anterobasal 3/5 of cell cup, basomedian 2/3 of alula and basal 1/6 of anal lobe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A8D210DBB8E36C8EAD85278162F54B29" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Legs: Black, except fifth tarsomeres brown; black pilose, except femora posterobasally white pilose and tarsi ventrally golden yellow pilose. Coxae black; white pilose. Trochanters brown; white pilose.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FDF8BE94FBD94EDECDC3A1349ED4F392" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Abdomen. Tergites black with faint metallic hues, except for a dull black fascia on anterior 2/5 of tergite 3 and a very narrow, medially interrupted dull black fascia along anterior margin of tergite 4. Tergites 1 and 2 yellowish white pilose. Tergites 3 and 4 black pilose, except white pilose posterolaterally. Sternites blackish brown; sternite 1 bare; sternite 2 yellow pilose; sternite 3 black pilose except yellow pilose along posterior margin; sternite 4 black pilose. Male genitalia as in Fig. 15.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE667728BDE3EA215A6CDF4E018D2637" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Female. 9.5 mm. As male, except for usual sexual differences. Tergite 5 black pilose, except white pilose posteriolaterally.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34BBE6F5E4A3F791CA537E5F54C73A99" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A4107C2213F171951D299A2E3257C4ED" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="828B9894BB627E3576485B779B9D8EFC" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">The specific epithet (adjective) is derived from Maluku, the group of islands to which Halmaheira, where the species was found, belongs.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
